Nairobi Storymoja Hay Festival: Defiance in the face of loss
Alice Vincent was at the Hay Festival Nairobi when terror struck. She hears the writers who refused to be silenced.
Storymoja Hay Festival: Professor Kofi Awoonor (inset), one of the guest speakers, died after sustaining injuries during the attack at Westgate shopping centre in Nairobi By Alice Vincent
12:38PM BST 30 Sep 2013
Follow Comments
Half way through the Storymoja Hay Festival I stopped concentrating. Two miles away, in the only part of Nairobi I had become familiar with during my short stay, militant Islamist group Al-Shabaab had opened fire on innocent people in the Westgate Mall. Helicopters flew overhead, and although normality prevailed around the festival tents, I felt a little sick, a little scared, a little short of breath. The speculated casualty numbers passed through Twitter to word of mouth around the National Museum of Kenya, the leafy, rambling location for the festival. By lunchtime 12 had died, shortly after it was 20. A cloak of confusion hung over us, as it did over the whole of Nairobi. The events were alien, but also horribly familiar; emerging from my memory as headlines from earlier terrorist attacks in London or New York. Heavy clouds drew in with the evening and the site emptied as emergency security was brought in. A handful of brave, stubborn speakers gave the talks they were in Nairobi to give, regardless of what their embassies told them. Notably, the African poets from Sierra Leone, Kenya, Uganda and Ghana, who went to perform without Ghanaian poet and diplomat Kofi Awoonor. The 78-year-old could not be reached. People said that he had gone to Westgate with his son earlier in the day. The one lesson I learned from it all, a heady, heart-wrenching mix, was to tell stories. During the festival’s opening Dr Auma Obama, activist and sister of the US President, stressed that “people need to write. Kenyans have wonderful stories to tell, we must share ourselves, share our stories.” Four days later, we reeled sleepless from the events that had passed and Kenyan storyteller Atinuke told me that I must write, and write beautifully, about my experience. Stories were a cradle of comfort in those 24 uncertain hours. The strength and efficiency of the festival’s organisers ensured that I rarely felt unsafe, shuttled from safe place to safe bed in the company of others. Our driver, Moses, navigated a path along Nairobi’s dusty and unlit roads, deftly avoiding the roadblocks and closures in the city. Unable to sleep, we sat up with tea and gin, depending on the time, and shared anecdotes against the insects’ calls in the forest nearby. Related Articles
