22 Sep 2013
Nairobi terror attack
21 Sep 2013
Travellers urged to stand by Kenya
26 Sep 2013
A few hours later we learned that Awoonor had died after sustaining injuries from the shooting. It was dizzying news that made the walls within which we were safely confined seem smaller. Storymoja is a friendly festival, and while I had not met Awoonor, we had shared the same spaces over the previous days. After arriving at the festival, I listened as he praised the diversity of African writers on the bill: “together we are discussing the birthing pains of countries.” None of us realised then how painfully prescient this statement would become. For this type of mourning, silence was not an option. Four days earlier, Storymoja founder Muthoni Garland had introduced the festival as “an unadulterated, unapologetic celebration of writing”. She showed the same strength by hosting an evening of reading and remembrance for Awoonor on the festival site on Monday, the siege still ongoing a short drive away. More than 150 people came, read, lit candles, a glimmer of hope that something good could come out of the atrocities that had so recently occurred. Although he had lost one of his country’s shining lights, the Ghanaian High Commissioner was undeterred. “Next year,” he told Garland, “I will bring you more writers from my country. That is what Kofi Awoonor would have wanted.” Other authors, Atinuke, Teju Cole and Jenny Valentine, insisted they wanted to return to the line-up next year, when Dr Obama will be Festival Director, to tell their stories in defiance of fear and loss. Follow @TelegraphBooks
